{{Infobox NRHP | name =Shelburne Farms | nrhp_type = nhld | nocat = yes | image = Shelburne Farm VT.jpg | caption = | location = [[Shelburne, Vermont|Shelburne]], [[Vermont|Vermont, USA]] | locmapin = Vermont#USA | coordinates = {{coord|44|23|31.69|N|73|15|26.04|W|display=inline,title}} | area = {{convert|1339|acre|ha}} | built =1887 | architect= Multiple; Robertson, Henderson Robert | architecture= Tudor Revival, Queen Anne, Other |designated_nrhp_type=January 3, 2001<ref name="nhlsum">{{cite web|url=http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1823955315&ResourceType=District |title=Shelburne Farms |accessdate=2008-06-25|work=National Historic Landmark summary listing|publisher=National Park Service}}</ref> | added = August 11, 1980 | governing_body = Local | refnum=80000330<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref> }}
'''Shelburne Farms''' is a nonprofit education center for sustainability, {{convert|1400|acre}} working farm, and [[National Historic Landmark]] on the shores of [[Lake Champlain]] in [[Shelburne, Vermont]]. The property is nationally significant as a well-preserved example of a [[Gilded Age]] "ornamental farm", developed in the late 19th century with architecture by [[Robert Henderson Robertson]] and landscaping by [[Frederick Law Olmsted]].
==Description and history== Shelburne Farms was created in 1886 by [[William Seward Webb|Dr. William Seward Webb]] and [[Eliza Osgood Vanderbilt Webb]] as a model agricultural estate, using money inherited from railroad magnate [[William Henry Vanderbilt]]. They commissioned landscape architect [[Frederick Law Olmsted]] to guide the layout of {{convert|3800|acre}} of farm, field and forest, and New York architect [[Robert Henderson Robertson]], to design the buildings. The estate was created by purchasing a large number of mostly agricultural properties, and then adapting the existing roads and lanes (some of which were public ways the Webbs petitioned to have closed) to fulfill the Webbs' vision for the estate.<ref name=nhl>{{cite web|url={{NHLS url|id=80000330}}|title=NHL nomination for Shelburne Farms|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=2015-04-18}}</ref> The property was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1980, and was designated a [[National Historic Landmark District]] in 2001.<ref name="nhlsum"/><ref name="nris"/>
Shelburne Farms was incorporated as a nonprofit educational organization in 1972 by descendants of the Webbs. Nearly {{convert|400|acre}} of sustainably managed woodlands received ''Green Certification'' from the [[Forest Stewardship Council]] in 1998. The farm's grass-based [[dairy]] supports a herd of 125 purebred, registered [[Brown Swiss]] [[cows]]. Their milk is made into farmhouse [[cheddar cheese]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shelburnefarms.org/about/cheesmakingawards.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-04-24 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060908012838/http://www.shelburnefarms.org/about/cheesmakingawards.htm |archivedate=2006-09-08 |df= }}</ref> The farm serves as an educational resource by practicing rural land use that is environmentally, economically and culturally [[Sustainability|sustainable]]. Visitors may enjoy the walking trails, children's farmyard, inn, restaurant, property tours and special events.
